# gitleaks false-positive baseline.
#
# gitleaks ignores findings by FINGERPRINT (not by pattern). A fingerprint looks like:
#   <commit-sha>:<file-path>:<rule-id>:<line-number>
# It is printed in gitleaks' report/output for each finding.
#
# When a confirmed false positive appears (e.g. a test fixture or example value), paste
# its fingerprint on its own line below to suppress it.
# Do NOT suppress a real secret - rotate it, then purge it from history instead.
#
# Example (commented out):
# 0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d:tests/fixtures/sample.env:generic-api-key:12
#
# 2026-07-17: two confirmed false positives from the `curl-auth-user` rule. The OpenCode
# cross-user security-verification docs contain the example line
# `curl ... -u opencode:verifypw http://127.0.0.1:.../app`, where `opencode:verifypw` is a
# documented THROWAWAY test credential (the disposable password created for the local
# server auth test), not a real secret. The files were later relocated to
# `.agents/prompts/reusable/`, but gitleaks scans full history so the original commit
# `1efe57d` still trips the rule.
